WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.184
Chronic lung disease of infancy, often
called bronchopulmonary dysplasia,

2
00:00:04.784 --> 00:00:09.505
is a condition you'll see in premature
infants who needed oxygen or ventilatory support

3
00:00:09.505 --> 00:00:10.404
early in life.

4
00:00:10.564 --> 00:00:12.704
But this isn't just a past problem.

5
00:00:13.185 --> 00:00:16.305
It's an ongoing issue of limited
respiratory reserve.

6
00:00:17.024 --> 00:00:17.864
Here's the key idea.

7
00:00:18.444 --> 00:00:21.165
These infants were born before their lungs
fully developed.

8
00:00:21.725 --> 00:00:26.344
When you combine immature alveoli with
oxygen exposure, positive pressure,

9
00:00:26.465 --> 00:00:29.504
and inflammation, you disrupt normal lung
growth.

10
00:00:30.325 --> 00:00:33.084
Instead of developing many small,
efficient alveoli,

11
00:00:33.205 --> 00:00:35.264
they end up with fewer, larger,

12
00:00:35.645 --> 00:00:38.865
less effective ones, and that means
reduced gas exchange.

13
00:00:39.505 --> 00:00:40.944
Clinically, think patterns.

14
00:00:41.205 --> 00:00:43.985
You'll see tachypnea, retractions, and a

15
00:00:43.985 --> 00:00:45.224
persistent need for oxygen.

16
00:00:45.724 --> 00:00:49.064
These infants often desaturate with
stress, especially feeding.

17
00:00:49.645 --> 00:00:50.044
Why?

18
00:00:50.444 --> 00:00:53.805
Because feeding increases oxygen demand,
and their lungs can't keep

19
00:00:53.805 --> 00:00:54.084
up.

20
00:00:54.424 --> 00:00:57.305
As an RT, your role is all about balance.

21
00:00:57.884 --> 00:01:01.685
You must provide enough oxygen to prevent
hypoxemia, which can

22
00:01:01.685 --> 00:01:06.004
worsen pulmonary hypertension, but avoid
excessive oxygen that contributes to

23
00:01:06.004 --> 00:01:06.404
lung injury.

24
00:01:06.944 --> 00:01:09.785
This is a tight window, and board
questions love testing

25
00:01:09.785 --> 00:01:10.444
that concept.

26
00:01:10.985 --> 00:01:12.944
You'll also monitor ventilation closely.

27
00:01:13.805 --> 00:01:16.224
Rising carbon dioxide, increasing work of
breathing,

28
00:01:16.985 --> 00:01:18.925
apnea, or bradycardia are red flags.

29
00:01:19.385 --> 00:01:21.165
These are not wait-and-see situations.

30
00:01:21.165 --> 00:01:23.345
These are escalate-now moments.

31
00:01:24.224 --> 00:01:27.745
Support strategies include oxygen therapy,
high-flow nasal cannula,

32
00:01:28.425 --> 00:01:30.544
CPAP, or mechanical ventilation if needed.

33
00:01:30.785 --> 00:01:33.625
But remember, the goal is always the least
invasive,

34
00:01:34.245 --> 00:01:37.504
least injurious support that maintains
adequate gas exchange.

35
00:01:38.105 --> 00:01:39.925
Another critical concept is trending.

36
00:01:40.444 --> 00:01:43.724
A single normal SpO2 doesn't mean the
patient is stable.

37
00:01:44.245 --> 00:01:47.584
You're looking at the whole picture—FiO2
needs, work of

38
00:01:47.584 --> 00:01:49.404
breathing, feeding tolerance, growth,

39
00:01:49.625 --> 00:01:50.425
and blood gases.

40
00:01:51.184 --> 00:01:52.544
And don't forget complications.

41
00:01:53.385 --> 00:01:57.105
Pulmonary hypertension is a major concern
in these patients, especially

42
00:01:57.105 --> 00:01:59.044
if hypoxemia is not well-controlled.

43
00:01:59.745 --> 00:02:02.724
So when you see a former preemie with
increasing oxygen needs,

44
00:02:03.305 --> 00:02:05.964
worsening retractions, or feeding
intolerance, think

45
00:02:05.964 --> 00:02:09.024
chronic lung disease of infancy, and act
early.

46
00:02:09.585 --> 00:02:10.184
Bottom line?

47
00:02:10.664 --> 00:02:12.585
This is a disease of limited reserve.

48
00:02:13.264 --> 00:02:14.205
Small changes matter.

49
00:02:14.205 --> 00:02:15.884
Early recognition matters.

50
00:02:16.365 --> 00:02:20.904
And your ability to assess trends and
respond appropriately can make a huge difference

51
00:02:20.904 --> 00:02:21.404
in outcomes.

